ng manual event recording and tag functionality. Testing metrics name constants raises questions about coverage too.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Exploring TimeLimiter testing options**\\\\n\\\\nI’m considering whether I can import MetricNames and assert constants, even if it isn't a functional feature. I’m also thinking about the current implementation of events and how they handle toString and eventName within the public API. There's a concern about the overlap in supplier tests with existing caching. It might be helpful to adjust the tests by not testing tags merging and instead using a no-tags supplier overload. I was thinking of ensuring we assert that supplier calls one time, while examining the overall caching mechanisms involved.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Refining tests for TimeLimiter**\\\\n\\\\nI’m trying to clarify how to test if the supplier isn’t called when absent. It seems like the supplier gets invoked with each call, and I need to ensure no tags are involved. If I test the second call, I’m introducing caching, but the unique name \\\\\\\"supplier only when absent\\\\\\\" suggests a different approach. To minimize duplication, I could remove tags merging. I’ll also want to incorporate the assertThat method for integer checks to make the tests clearer.\\\"}]}\"}, {\"type\": \"toolCall\", \"id\": \"call_oFp9GJIlqASfs2S4U6eSDqYQ|fc_0f593d492f4fd13a0169fd03a8aa04819c8d0a2e231a91baae\", \"name\": \"edit\", \"arguments\": {\"path\": \"tests/src/io.github.resilience4j/resilience4j-timelimiter/2.3.0/src/test/java/io_github_resilience4j/resilience4j_timelimiter/Resilience4j_timelimiterTest.java\", \"edits\": [{\"oldText\": \"    @Test\\n    void registryCreatesTimeLimiterFromConfigSupplierOnlyWhenEntryIsAbsent() {\\n        TimeLimiterConfig suppliedConfig = TimeLimiterConfig.custom()\\n            .timeoutDuration(Duration.ofMillis(150))\\n            .cancelRunningFuture(false)\\n            .build();\\n        TimeLimiterRegistry registry = TimeLimiterRegistry.of(\\n            Map.of(), Map.of(\\\"scope\\\", \\\"registry\\\", \\\"shared\\\", \\\"from-registry\\\"));\\n        AtomicInteger supplierCalls = new AtomicInteger();\\n\\n        TimeLimiter created = registry.timeLimiter(\\\"shipping\\\", () -> {\\n            supplierCalls.incrementAndGet();\\n            return suppliedConfig;\\n        }, Map.of(\\\"team\\\", \\\"fulfillment\\\", \\\"shared\\\", \\\"from-instance\\\"));\\n        TimeLimiter cached = registry.timeLimiter(\\\"shipping\\\", () -> {\\n            supplierCalls.incrementAndGet();\\n            return TimeLimiterConfig.ofDefaults();\\n        });\\n\\n        assertThat(cached).isSameAs(created);\\n        assertThat(supplierCalls).hasValue(1);\\n        assertThat(created.getTimeLimiterConfig()).isSameAs(suppliedConfig);\\n        assertThat(created.getTags())\\n            .containsEntry(\\\"scope\\\", \\\"registry\\\")\\n            .containsEntry(\\\"team\\\", \\\"fulfillment\\\")\\n            .containsEntry(\\\"shared\\\", \\\"from-instance\\\");\\n    }\\n\", \"newText\": \"    @Test\\n    void registryCreatesTimeLimiterFromConfigSupplierOnlyWhenEntryIsAbsent() {\\n        TimeLimiterConfig suppliedConfig = TimeLimiterConfig.custom()\\n            .timeoutDuration(Duration.ofMillis(150))\\n            .cancelRunningFuture(false)\\n            .build();\\n        TimeLimiterRegistry registry = TimeLimiterRegistry.ofDefaults();\\n        AtomicInteger supplierCalls = new AtomicInteger();\\n\\n        TimeLimiter created = registry.timeLimiter(\\\"shipping\\\", () -> {\\n            supplierCalls.incrementAndGet();\\n            return suppliedConfig;\\n        });\\n        TimeLimiter cached = registry.timeLimiter(\\\"shipping\\\", () -> {\\n            supplierCalls.incrementAndGet();\\n            return TimeLimiterConfig.ofDefaults();\\n        });\\n\\n        assertThat(cached).isSameAs(created);\\n        assertThat(s